ABSTRACT

Milk Production and Prediction System is a web-based dairy-farm management platform developed to support the day-to-day operations of dairy farms while also connecting farm owners, workers, and customers through a single digital system. The current implementation focuses on managing farm records, cattle data, sheds, workers, milk entry, milk availability, customer orders, and subscription-based milk purchases. By bringing these activities together in one platform, the project improves operational visibility, reduces manual coordination, and supports a more organized milk distribution workflow.

The system provides role-based access for different users, including farm owners, workers, and customers. Farm owners can manage farms, maintain cattle records, assign workers, organize sheds, review milk collection data, and handle incoming customer requests. Workers can participate in farm operations through the assigned workflows, while customers can browse available milk, place one-time orders, and create recurring subscriptions. The platform also supports order and subscription approval flows, giving farm owners control over fulfillment and customer engagement.

From a technical perspective, the project uses a React-based frontend built with Vite and a Spring Boot backend backed by MySQL for persistent data storage. Redis is included for caching support, and JWT-based authentication with Spring Security is used to secure protected application routes and APIs. The frontend includes multilingual support and interfaces for core operational tasks, while the backend exposes structured APIs for authentication, farms, cattle, milk inventory, orders, subscriptions, sheds, and user management.

The repository also reflects a deployment-oriented architecture. Containerization is supported through Docker, while Kubernetes deployment resources are managed with Helm charts. Infrastructure provisioning is prepared with Terraform, and the project includes CI/CD-related configuration through Jenkins and Argo CD resources. Together, these elements make the system suitable not only as an academic software project but also as a practical foundation for scalable dairy management and digital milk service operations.

This abstract presents the current scope of the project as implemented in the repository. It serves as a concise summary of the system's purpose, functional coverage, technical foundation, and deployment readiness, without extending into introductory or future-planning material.